y `{}` instead of a list. I'll handle that by treating any non-list input as empty or invalid and returning True if it's empty or contains no dictionaries.\n\nHere's the function:\n\n```python\ndef empty_dit(lst):\n    # If input is not a list, treat empty dict as True, else False\n    if not isinstance(lst, list):\n        return lst == {}\n    # Check if all elements are dictionaries and empty\n    return all(isinstance(d, dict) and len(d) == 0 for d in lst)\n```\n\nTesting with your assertions (correcting the second test case):\n\n```python\nassert empty_dit([{}, {}, {}]) == True\nassert empty_dit([{1: None, 2: None}, {}, {}]) == False\nassert empty_dit({}) == True\n```\n\nThis function returns True only if all elements in the list are empty dictionaries. If the input is a dictionary (not a list), it returns True only if it's empty."}
